value.value: A gene related to a similar gene by duplication within a genome.

A compound that mimics the naturally occurring polyamines but is modified in such a way that its function differs from that of the natural polyamines and is usually biologically inactive. Polyamine analogues most likely exert their actions through their ability to displace the natural polyamines from their DNA binding sites. Since the natural polyamines are involved in numerous important cellular processes such as cell division, differentiation and membrane function, their displacement from the DNA binding site may lead to an inhibition of cell growth.
A malignant epithelial tumor of the stomach mucosa. The vast majority of gastric carcinomas are adenocarcinomas, arising from the gastric glandular epithelium.
A morphologic variant of angioleiomyoma characterized by the presence of numerous small, slit-like vascular channels.
A morphologic variant of angioleiomyoma characterized by the presence of thick-walled veins.
A morphologic variant of angioleiomyoma characterized by the presence of markedly dilated vascular channels.
The thin layer of smooth muscle surrounding the scrotum which contracts or expands the scrotal skin to regulate testicular temperature.

A carcinoma arising from the bladder epithelium.  Approximately 90% of the bladder carcinomas are transitional cell carcinomas.  The remainder are squamous cell carcinomas, adenocarcinomas and small cell neuroendocrine carcinomas.

A classification of subtypes of ischemic stroke based on clinical features and the results of ancillary diagnostic studies.The TOAST classification denotes five subtypes of ischemic stroke: 1) large-artery atherosclerosis, 2) cardioembolism, 3) small-vessel occlusion, 4) stroke of other determined etiology, and 5) stroke of undetermined etiology.
Used to associate a drug with its various salt forms.
Used to associate the salt form of a drug with its free acid or free base.

label.value: Intersecting Sharply Marginated Clusters of Spindle Cells Present
Malignant Smooth Muscle Cell with Granular Cytoplasmic Change

value.value: This gene is involved in chromatin remodeling and regulation of gene transcription.

A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the female reproductive system.  Representative examples include endometrial carcinoma, cervical carcinoma, ovarian carcinoma, uterine corpus leiomyosarcoma, adenosarcoma, malignant mixed mesodermal (mullerian) tumor, and gestational choriocarcinoma.
Remodeling and spacing factor 1 (1441 aa, ~164 kDa) is encoded by the human RSF1 gene. This protein is involved in chromatin remodeling.
A diagnostic test used to examine and define microscopic tissue structure, composition, or etiology. The test results are often used by a clinician to diagnose disease or disordered function.
A diagnostic test utilized to examine and define cellular anatomy or function. The test results are often used by a clinician to diagnose disease or disordered function.
Surgical removal of both non-diseased ovaries with the goal of preventing ovarian carcinoma.
To stop a process by imposing a freeze on it.
A new drug or biological drug that is used in a clinical investigation. The term also includes a biological product that is used in vitro for diagnostic purposes.

label.value: Cortical Cell Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: Cerebral tissue composed of cells with distinctive characteristics. The cerebral cortex contains six cell layers.

label.value: Cortical Cell Layer of the Cerebellum

value.value: The cortical cell layer of the cerebellum. It consists of the granular layer, molecular layer, and Purkinje cell layer.
A carcinoma that arises from the skin.  Representative examples are basal cell carcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma.

label.value: Purkinje Cell Layer of the Cerebellum
Internal Granular Layer of the Cerebellum

value.value: The number of molecules of a particular type on or in a cell or part of a cell. Usually applied to specific genes or to plasmids within a bacterium.

A type of evaluation that is primarily descriptive and interpretative, and may or may not lend itself to quantification. Mainly concerned with the properties, the state, and the character (i.e., the nature) of phenomena. It implies an emphasis on processes and meanings that are rigorously examined, but not measured in terms of quantity, amount, or frequency. (www.unfpa.org/monitoring/toolkit/glossary.pdf and Nonprofit Good Practice Guide Glossary)
A computerized library of tests designed for baseline screening and serial assessment of neurocognitive function.
The quality of nearness to the truth or the true value.
A class of viral vaccines based on adenovirus genome which was engineered to harbor gene of therapeutic interest, and were to be used in vaccination against cancers.
The act of touching physically; the physical coming together of two or more things.
An outcome or conclusion that can be arrived at by measurement.
A statement (either spoken or written) that is made in reply to a question or request or criticism or accusation; a statement that solves a problem or explains how to solve the problem.

label.value: Embryonal Tumor with Multilayered Rosettes, C19MC-Altered

value.value: An aggressive embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes characterized by the presence of amplification of the C19MC region on chromosome 19 (19q13.42).
The magnitude of something in a third direction, generally representing depth.

A fetus of at least 20 weeks gestation, or of a birth weight of at least 350 grams if the gestational age is unknown, that is born without signs of life at the time of delivery, and with an Apgar score of zero at both one and five minutes.
A problem requiring investigation.
